      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Read this entire manual before operating the machine.</strong> Untrained users can be seriously hurt. Only allow trained or properly supervised people to use the sander.
      </div>

      <h3>General Safety</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Always wear ANSI-approved safety glasses or a face shield when operating or observing.</li>
        <li>Dust created while sanding may cause cancer, birth defects, or long-term respiratory damage. Always wear a NIOSH-approved respirator.</li>
        <li>Always wear hearing protection when operating.</li>
        <li>Do not wear loose clothing, gloves, or jewelry. Tie back long hair.</li>
        <li>Never operate under the influence of drugs or alcohol, or when fatigued.</li>
        <li>Disconnect power before servicing, adjusting, or changing sandpaper.</li>
        <li>Do not use in wet, cluttered, or poorly-lit areas. Keep work area clean and dry.</li>
        <li>Do not force the machine. It works best at its designed rate.</li>
        <li>Keep proper footing and balance. Do not overreach.</li>
        <li>Never leave the machine running unattended.</li>
        <li>Regularly inspect for damaged parts, loose bolts, and worn cords or plugs.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Disc Sander Safety</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Sand on the downward-moving side only.</strong> Only sand on the left side of the disc where it rotates downward. Sanding on the upward-moving right side risks workpiece kick-out and abrasion injuries.</li>
        <li>Keep hands away from the sandpaper during operation. Rotating sandpaper can remove flesh in seconds.</li>
        <li>Always use a jig or holding device when sanding small workpieces. Keep hands at least 2&quot; from the sanding surface.</li>
        <li>Always sand with the workpiece firmly against the table or another support device.</li>
        <li>Ease the workpiece slowly into the sandpaper with light pressure. Forcefully jamming can pull hands into the sanding surface.</li>
        <li>Inspect sandpaper before use and replace if worn or damaged.</li>
        <li>Adjust the table no more than 1/16&quot; from the sandpaper to prevent finger or workpiece entrapment.</li>
        <li>Only sand solid workpieces that can withstand power sanding forces. Avoid workpieces without flat bottom surfaces unless using a jig.</li>
        <li>Inspect all workpieces for nails, staples, or other embedded foreign objects before sanding.</li>
      </ol>

