      <h2>Setup</h2>

      <h3>Unpacking &amp; Cleaning</h3>
      <p>The table and unpainted parts are coated with a waxy grease for corrosion protection during shipment. Clean with a solvent cleaner or citrus-based degreaser. Do not use chlorine-based solvents (brake cleaner, acetone) as they will ruin painted surfaces.</p>

      <h3>Machine Placement</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/shop-fox-w1828/p20_00.jpg" alt="Working clearances diagram showing 18 inch width, 17-1/4 inch depth, and minimum 3 inch air gap behind the motor" />
        <figcaption>Working clearances</figcaption>
      </div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Workbench load:</strong> The machine concentrates 68 lbs in a small footprint. Some workbenches may need additional bracing.</li>
        <li><strong>Clearances:</strong> Allow space for material handling, the dust hose, and at least 3&quot; of air gap behind the motor.</li>
        <li><strong>Lighting:</strong> Bright enough to eliminate shadows and prevent eye strain.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Bench Mounting</h3>
      <p>Mount the sander to a workbench to prevent movement during operation. Remove the included rubber feet before mounting.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Through mount (strongest):</strong> Drill holes through the workbench. Use hex bolts, flat washers, lock washers, and hex nuts to secure.</li>
        <li><strong>Direct mount:</strong> Secure with lag screws and flat washers directly into the workbench surface.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Dust Collection</h3>
      <div class="note">
        <strong>Recommended CFM at dust port: 98 CFM.</strong> Do not confuse this with the dust collector&rsquo;s overall CFM rating. Actual CFM at the port depends on hose length, branches, and other open lines in the system.
      </div>
      <p>Connect a 2&quot; hose to the dust port. Optionally use a 4&quot; x 2&quot; adapter to connect to a 4&quot; main line.</p>

      <div class="danger">
        Do not operate without adequate dust collection. This machine creates substantial wood dust that can cause short and long-term respiratory illness.
      </div>

      <h3>Test Run</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Clear all tools and objects from the machine.</li>
        <li>Turn the machine ON. It should run smoothly with little vibration or rubbing noises. Investigate any unusual sounds before proceeding.</li>
        <li>Turn the machine OFF.</li>
        <li>Remove the switch disabling key and try to start the machine. It should not start. If it does, the switch is defective&mdash;contact Tech Support.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Operations</h2>

      <h3>Choosing Sandpaper</h3>
      <p>The W1828 uses 12&quot; adhesive-backed (PSA) sanding discs. Aluminum oxide is recommended for general use.</p>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><th>Grit Range</th><th>Type</th></tr>
          <tr><td>24&ndash;36</td><td>Very Coarse</td></tr>
          <tr><td>40&ndash;60</td><td>Coarse</td></tr>
          <tr><td>80&ndash;100</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
          <tr><td>120&ndash;180</td><td>Fine</td></tr>
          <tr><td>220&ndash;360</td><td>Very Fine</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>Sand with progressively higher grits, increasing no more than 50 grits at a time. Do not skip grits.</p>

      <h3>Attaching Sandpaper</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/manuals/shop-fox-w1828/p23_00.jpg" alt="Slipping the half-covered sandpaper disc between the sanding disc and the table edge" />
        <img src="/manuals/shop-fox-w1828/p23_01.jpg" alt="Peeling off the remaining paper backing from the sandpaper disc" />
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Disconnect the machine from power.</li>
        <li>Peel off the old sandpaper and clean the disc surface with mineral spirits. Wipe dry.</li>
        <li>Peel back the protective layer on one half of the new disc and fold it against the remaining half.</li>
        <li>Slip the covered half between the disc and the table edge.</li>
        <li>Position the exposed adhesive half over the aluminum disc above the table and press firmly.</li>
        <li>Rotate the disc so the lower half is above the table, peel off the remaining backing, and press firmly to complete adhesion.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Disc Sanding</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/manuals/shop-fox-w1828/p24_00.jpg" alt="90-degree disc sanding with workpiece flat against the table" />
        <img src="/manuals/shop-fox-w1828/p24_01.jpg" alt="Miter sanding with workpiece against the miter gauge at an angle" />
        <img src="/manuals/shop-fox-w1828/p24_02.jpg" alt="Sanding with the table tilted at an angle" />
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Disconnect the sander from power.</li>
        <li>Set the table angle and miter gauge for your operation. Ensure the table is about 1/16&quot; from the sanding disc.</li>
        <li>Connect to power, turn ON, and allow the disc to reach full speed.</li>
        <li>Position the workpiece on the table against the miter gauge.</li>
        <li>With light but firm pressure, push the workpiece into the <strong>down-spin side</strong> (left side) of the rotating disc.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        Move the workpiece slowly back and forth from the left side to the center to wear the sandpaper evenly and prevent burning. For compound-angle cuts, tilt the table and rotate the miter gauge to the appropriate angles.
      </div>

      <h3>Stock Inspection</h3>
      <p>Before sanding, inspect all workpieces for:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Material type:</strong> Do not sand workpieces containing asbestos or lead paint.</li>
        <li><strong>Foreign objects:</strong> Nails, staples, dirt, or rocks will tear the sandpaper. Remove or reject the workpiece.</li>
        <li><strong>Excessive glue or finish:</strong> Will load up the abrasive, reducing its life.</li>
      </ul>

