      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <h3>General Inspection</h3>
      <div class="warning">
        Always disconnect the machine from power before performing maintenance.
      </div>
      <p>Before each use, check for:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Loose mounting bolts</li>
        <li>Worn switch</li>
        <li>Worn or damaged cords and plugs</li>
        <li>Worn or damaged sandpaper</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Cleaning</h3>
      <p>Frequently vacuum wood chips and sawdust, then blow off remaining dust with compressed air. Pay special attention to the motor&mdash;sawdust buildup shortens motor life.</p>

      <h3>Lubrication</h3>
      <p>All bearings are sealed and permanently lubricated. Do not lubricate them. Keep cast-iron table surfaces rust-free with products like SLIPIT or Boeshield T-9 for long-term storage.</p>

      <h2>Service &amp; Calibration</h2>

      <h3>Table/Disc Parallelism</h3>
      <p>The table edge must be parallel to the sanding disc face with a 1/16&quot; gap&mdash;large enough so sandpaper doesn&rsquo;t rub the table, but small enough to avoid a pinch hazard.</p>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/shop-fox-w1828/p25_00.jpg" alt="Table parallel with sanding disc showing 1/16 inch gap and flat head screws" />
        <figcaption>Table/disc parallelism adjustment</figcaption>
      </div>
      <p><strong>Tools needed:</strong> 10mm wrench, #2 Phillips screwdriver, fine ruler.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Disconnect from power.</li>
        <li>Loosen the six flat head screws and hex nuts securing the table to the support brackets.</li>
        <li>Adjust the table for a 1/16&quot; gap between the 12&quot; disc (with sandpaper) and the table, left to right.</li>
        <li>Tighten the screws and nuts.</li>
        <li>Spin the disc by hand to verify the sandpaper doesn&rsquo;t touch the table. Repeat if it does.</li>
        <li>Follow with miter gauge calibration (below).</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Miter Gauge Calibration</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/manuals/shop-fox-w1828/p25_01.jpg" alt="Using a try square to check that the miter gauge face is perpendicular to the sanding disc" />
        <img src="/manuals/shop-fox-w1828/p25_02.jpg" alt="Squaring the table to the sanding disc face using a try square" />
      </div>
      <p><strong>Tools needed:</strong> Try or machinist&rsquo;s square, #1 Phillips screwdriver.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Disconnect from power.</li>
        <li>Place the square with one edge against the miter gauge face and the other against the disc.</li>
        <li>Loosen the lock knob, adjust the gauge face flush with the square, and retighten.</li>
        <li>Loosen the degree scale pointer, position it on 90&deg;, and retighten.</li>
        <li>Re-check accuracy with the square.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Table Tilt Calibration</h3>
      <p><strong>Tools needed:</strong> Try or machinist&rsquo;s square.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Disconnect from power.</li>
        <li>Set the square on the table with the other edge against the disc face.</li>
        <li>Loosen the tilt lock handles and adjust the table until perpendicular to the disc. Tighten while holding in place.</li>
        <li>If the angle pointers don&rsquo;t read 0&deg;, reposition the pointer stickers on the trunnion.</li>
        <li>Recheck with the square.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Problem</th><th>Possible Cause</th><th>Corrective Action</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td rowspan="4">Machine does not start</td><td>Switch disabling key removed</td><td>Re-install key</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Break or short in wiring</td><td>Trace and replace broken wires, fix connections</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Blown fuse / tripped breaker</td><td>Correct overload cause, reset breaker</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Motor or capacitor at fault</td><td>Test and replace if needed</td></tr>
          <tr><td rowspan="3">Excessive vibration or noise</td><td>Motor mounting loose</td><td>Tighten mounting bolts with thread-locking fluid</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Table tilt lock handle loose</td><td>Tighten the lock handle</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Motor bearings worn</td><td>Replace bearings or motor</td></tr>
          <tr><td rowspan="3">Machine stalls or slows</td><td>Too much feed pressure</td><td>Reduce pressure</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Motor overheated</td><td>Let cool, clean motor, reduce workload</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Warped or incorrect workpiece</td><td>Straighten or use a different workpiece</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Miter bar loose or binds</td><td>Miter slot dirty or gummed up</td><td>Clean the miter slot</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Workpiece angle incorrect</td><td>Miter gauge or table not calibrated</td><td>Recalibrate (see Service section above)</td></tr>
          <tr><td rowspan="3">Sandpaper clogs or burns</td><td>Grit too fine for the job</td><td>Use coarser grit</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Workpiece too moist</td><td>Allow workpiece to dry</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Paint/varnish/pitch loading</td><td>Strip coating first or use coarser grit</td></tr>
          <tr><td rowspan="2">Glossy spots or streaks</td><td>Work held still too long</td><td>Keep workpiece moving across the disc</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Worn sandpaper</td><td>Replace sandpaper</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

